From Bruce Sidari Subject Re A question about outlet In article writes In article Russ Crisp writes I'm considering modernizing some old wiring in my home and I need a little advice on outlet Several outlets are the old 'two prong' type without the Naturally the wire feeding these outlets is WITHOUT the ground I noticed at the fusebox that some circuits have the with ground and that on these circuits the ground wire was tied to the same bus as the neutral white They are supposed to be connected together at the breaker but nowhere repeat NOwhere Well There are strange exceptions for things like sub Jamie Hanrahan Kernel Mode Systems San Diego CA Internet Uucp uunet cmkrnl jeh CIS Not even in sub panels The only place the neutral should be connected to the ground is in a SERVICE DISCONNECT In your house the main panel serves as the service Sub panles in your garage or workshop for example must maintain seperate neutral and ground busses because they are not service disconnect Steve Woodard not a licensed electrician but I can read the NEC my brother is though